# CAPM Curriculum (PMI-Aligned, Plain Language)

## Overview

This document outlines the current recognized curriculum for the
Certified Associate in Project Management (CAPM). It is based on the
Project Management Institute (PMI) Exam Content Outline.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Project Management Fundamentals and Core Concepts (36%)

### What this includes:

-   Difference between projects and ongoing work (operations)
-   Project lifecycle (start to finish)
-   Roles (project manager, team, stakeholders)
-   Basic planning, execution, and monitoring
-   Problem-solving approaches

### What this means:

You understand how a project works from beginning to end.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 2. Predictive (Plan-Based) Methods (17%)

### What this includes:

-   Defining project scope (what is included)
-   Creating task breakdowns
-   Scheduling work and timelines
-   Budget basics
-   Risk planning
-   Quality control

### What this means:

You can plan a project step-by-step before starting.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 3. Agile (Flexible) Methods (20%)

### What this includes:

-   Working in short cycles
-   Adapting to change
-   Continuous improvement
-   Team collaboration

### What this means:

You can manage projects where requirements change frequently.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4. Business Analysis (27%)

### What this includes:

-   Understanding what stakeholders need
-   Gathering and defining requirements
-   Connecting project work to business goals
-   Making sure the project delivers value

### What this means:

You understand why the project exists and what success looks like.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Key Idea

All CAPM learning should connect to one of these four areas: 1.
Understanding projects 2. Planning projects 3. Adapting to change 4.
Defining goals and value

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## How to Use This

When studying or practicing: - Identify which area the topic belongs
to - Focus on how it applies in real situations - Avoid memorizing
without understanding

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Path to PMP (Next Level)

The Project Management Professional (PMP) certification uses the same
areas, but focuses more on: - Making decisions - Handling complex
situations - Managing trade-offs

CAPM = understanding\
PMP = applying judgment
